# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: regius-professor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The **ancient universities** are a set of seven surviving British and Irish medieval universities and early modern universities that were founded before 1600 AD, and are located in Scotland, England, and Ireland.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] These ancient universities in Great Britain and Ireland are amongst the oldest extant universities in the world.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The ancient universities in Britain are also among twenty-seven institutions recognised by the British monarchy as privileged bodies of the United Kingdom.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] In the Middle Ages, universities followed the canonical hours of the church.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] As the masters in the arts faculty would often also be students in one of the higher faculties, universities used these canonical hours to define periods when the compulsory lectures in the different facilities were given in order to prevent timetable clashes.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] At Cambridge, for example, only the canon lawyers could lecture between *prime* (dawn) and *nones* (mid afternoon).
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] In the morning, there were lectures offered by regent masters on standard texts that they wanted to lecture.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Then in the afternoon there would be advanced bachelors that would give lectures that reviews the material learned that morning.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Also in the afternoon, the junior masters would discuss about other books of mathematical science or natural philosophy.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] These universities are often governed in a quite different fashion to more recent foundations.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The ancient universities of Scotland also share several distinctive features and are governed by arrangements laid down by the *Universities (Scotland) Acts*.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] In addition to these universities, some now-defunct institutions were founded during this period, including the University of Northampton (1261–1265), University of Stamford, Lincolnshire (1333–1335), and the University of Fraserburgh, Aberdeenshire (1592–1605).
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] There was also the medieval University of Dublin which was an early but largely unsuccessful attempt to establish a university in Dublin, the capital city of the Lordship of Ireland.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Founded in 1320, it maintained an intermittent existence for the next two centuries, but it never flourished, and disappeared for good at the Reformation in Ireland (1534–41).
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] It was located in St Patrick's Cathedral, Dublin.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] It had no connection with the present University of Dublin, better known as Trinity College Dublin (its sole college), which was founded in 1592.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The ancient universities are distinctive in awarding the Magister Artium/Master of Arts (MA) as an undergraduate academic degree.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] This is commonly known as the **Oxbridge MA**, **Trinity MA** (Dublin), or the **Scottish MA**.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The ancient universities in Scotland confer the MA degree at graduation with honours and a final mark; in contrast, the ancient universities in England and Ireland award the MA purely after a period of good standing following graduation as Bachelor of Arts, usually around three years.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Because they award the MA as an undergraduate Arts degree, the ancient universities award differing titles for their postgraduate master's degrees in the Arts and Humanities, such as the taught Master of Letters ("MLitt (T)").
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Some confusion can arise as to whether such degrees are taught degrees or the most established (and advanced) two-year research degrees, although this is often specified.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] While both universities received grants of liberties and privileges by royal charter, the charters granted to Cambridge in 1231 and to Oxford in 1248 being the earliest recorded on the Privy Councils list of chartered bodies, neither university was created or incorporated by royal charter.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] After existing for the first few centuries of their existence as common law corporations, they were formally incorporated by the Oxford and Cambridge Act 1571, under Elizabeth I.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The Universities of Oxford and Cambridge Act 1859 repealed the parts of the 1571 act that required the mayor, aldermen, citizens or municipal officer of the City of Oxford to take any oath for the conservation of the liberties and privileges of the University of Oxford.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Parliament passed the Chantries Act in 1545, which transferred ownership of all chantries and their properties to King Henry VIII.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Members of the University of Cambridge sent letters to the king's wife, Catherine Parr, about the potential threat this posed to the university.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] It is evident that the king already had special plans for the universities of Oxford and Cambridge, and that they were given special treatment compared to the other schools of England.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] At Cambridge, for example, King Henry VIII founded Trinity College, which would later become an important part of the University.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] In the 19th century a series of acts and commissions reduced the powers of the universities to make their own statutes.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] A Royal Commission in 1850 looked into both universities and proposed major reforms to their constitutions.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] These were enacted by the Oxford University Act 1854 and the Cambridge University Act 1856.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The Universities Tests Act 1871 removed almost all religious tests from both universities (and from Durham University).
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The Oxford and Cambridge Universities Act 1877 set up commissioners to look into further reform of the statutes of both universities and of their constituent colleges.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Further Royal Commissions into both universities were established in 1919, resulting in the Oxford and Cambridge Universities Act 1923, setting up a commission to again make statutes and regulations for the universities and their colleges.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The Universities (Scotland) Acts created a distinctive system of governance for the ancient universities in Scotland, the process beginning with the 1858 Act and ending with the 1966 Act.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Despite not being founded until after the first in these series of Acts, the University of Dundee shares all the features contained therein.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] As a result of these Acts, each of these universities is governed by a tripartite system of General Council, University Court, and Academic Senate.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The chief executive and chief academic is the University Principal who also holds the title of Vice-Chancellor as an honorific.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The Chancellor is a titular non-resident head to each university and is elected for life by the respective General Council, although in actuality a good number of Chancellors resign before the end of their 'term of office'.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Each also has a students' representative council as required by statute, although at the University of Aberdeen this has recently been renamed the *Students' Association Council*.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Which of the 19th-century institutions should be considered the earliest post-ancient university is a matter of debate.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Only Durham, London and the Queen's University of Ireland were recognised as universities at the time of their foundation, granting their first degrees in 1837, 1839 and 1851 respectively.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] Durham was a collegiate university, London was an examining board, and the Queen's University was a federal university.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The other institutions, while teaching at university level, were colleges, some becoming universities later.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The redbrick universities were established as university colleges in the latter half of the 19th century and mostly became universities in the early 20th century.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The Royal University of Ireland (1881, as the successor of the Queen's University of Ireland), the Victoria University (1881), and the University of Wales (1893) were the only other universities established in the 1800s, all as federal or examining universities.
[src:regius-professor/ancient-university] The first unitary university in the British Isles outside of Scotland was the University of Birmingham (1900).
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] The journal began publishing on 3 October 1840 as the *Provincial Medical and Surgical Journal* and quickly attracted the attention of physicians around the world through its publication of high-quality original research articles and unique case reports.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] Hennis Green, lecturer on the diseases of children at the Hunterian School of Medicine, who also was its founder, and Robert Streeten of Worcester, a member of the Provincial Medical and Surgical Association council.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] The first issue of the *Provincial Medical and Surgical Journal* (*PMSJ*) was 16 pages long and contained three simple woodcut illustrations.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] The longest items were the editors' introductory editorial and a report of the Provincial Medical and Surgical Association's Eastern Branch.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] Other pages included a condensed version of Henry Warburton's medical reform bill, book reviews, clinical papers, and case notes.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] There were 2+1⁄2 columns of advertisements.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] Inclusive of stamp duty it cost 7d, a price that remained until 1844.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In their introductory editorial and later statements, Green and Streeten defined "the main objects of promotion of which the *Provincial Medical and Surgical Journal* is established".
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] Summarized, there were two clear main objectives: the advancement of the profession, especially in the provinces, and dissemination of medical knowledge.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In April 1842 the journal was retitled the *Provincial Medical Journal and Retrospect of the Medical Sciences*, but two years later it reverted to the *PMSJ* under the sole editorship of Streeten.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In 1857 the *BMJ* first appeared, when the *PMSJ* was merged with the *Associated Medical Journal* (Volumes 1–4; 1853–1856), which had itself evolved from the *London Medical Journal* (Volumes 1–4; 1849–1852) under the editorship of John Rose Cormack.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In 1980, the journal split in two parts - *British medical journal (Clinical research edition)* [ISSN 0267-0623] and *British medical journal (Practice observed edition)* [ISSN 0267-0631].
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] A special "Christmas Edition" is published annually on the Friday before Christmas.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] This edition is known for research articles which apply a serious academic approach to investigating less serious medical questions.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] The results are often humorous and widely reported by the mainstream media.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] At the beginning of February 2021, *The BMJ* introduced a charge of £299 for publishing obituaries.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] This was widely criticized on social media, by the British Medical Association among others, because of the large number of medical staff being killed by COVID-19.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] The decision was explained, but reversed, by the end of the month.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In response to the many problems with traditional medical guidelines, the journal introduced *BMJ Rapid Recommendations*, a series of trustworthy guidelines focused on the most pressing medical problems.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] The five journals that cited *The BMJ* most often in 2008 were (in order of descending citation frequency) *The BMJ*, the *Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews*, *The Lancet*, *BMC Public Health*, and *BMC Health Services Research*.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In the same year the five journals most often cited in articles published in *The BMJ* were *The BMJ*, *The Lancet*, *The New England Journal of Medicine*, *Journal of the American Medical Association* and the *Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews*.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In the 2025 *Journal Citation Reports* *The BMJ's* impact factor was reported to be 55.1. ranking it 4th among the research journals in the general medical category.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In 1974, Elaine Murphy submitted a brief case report under her husband's name John which suggested a condition known as "cello scrotum", a fictional condition that supposedly affected male cellists.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] It was originally submitted as a joke in response to "guitar nipple", a condition similar to jogger's nipple in which some forms of guitar playing causes irritation to the nipple, which Murphy and her husband believed was also a joke.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In 2009, 35 years after the original case report was published, Murphy wrote a letter to *The BMJ* revealing that the report had been a hoax.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In 1999, all content of *The BMJ* was made freely available online; however, in 2006 this changed to a subscription model.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] Original research articles continue to be available free, but from January 2006 all other "added value" contents, including clinical reviews and editorials, require a subscription.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] *The BMJ* allows complete free access for visitors from economically disadvantaged countries as part of the HINARI initiative.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] In October 2008 *The BMJ* announced that it would become an open access journal for research articles.
[src:regius-professor/british-medical-journal] A subscription continued to be required for access to other articles.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The **Cabinet Office** is the ministerial department and senior decision-making office of the Government of the United Kingdom, responsible for supporting the prime minister and Cabinet.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The Cabinet Office is also the corporate headquarters of the British Civil Service and it is composed of various units that support Cabinet committees and coordinate the delivery of government objectives via other departments.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] As of March 2026, it had more than 5,385 staff, mostly civil servants, many of whom work in Whitehall and Canary Wharf.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] Staff working in the Prime Minister's Office, 10 Downing Street, are part of the Cabinet Office.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The department was formed in December 1916 from the secretariat of the Committee of Imperial Defence under Sir Maurice Hankey, the first Cabinet Secretary.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] Traditionally, the most important part of the Cabinet Office's role was facilitating collective decision-making by the Cabinet, through running and supporting Cabinet-level committees.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] This is still its principal role, but since the absorption of some of the functions of the Civil Service Department in 1981 the Cabinet Office has also helped to ensure that a wide range of Ministerial priorities are taken forward across Whitehall.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] It also contains miscellaneous units that do not sit well in other departments.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] In modern times, the Cabinet Office often takes on responsibility for areas of policy which are the priority of the Government of the time.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The units that administer these areas migrate in and out of the Cabinet Office as government priorities (and governments) change.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] Since 2016 the size of the Cabinet Office and the UK Civil Service has grown due to new responsibilities after Brexit and also during the Covid pandemic.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] In 2025 the UK Government announced a reduction on numbers which will hope to save £110m a year by 2028.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The Cabinet Office also supports the work of the Whips' Offices of the House of Lords and House of Commons.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The Parliamentary Private Secretary to the Cabinet Office supports the work of ministers.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The main building of the Cabinet Office is at 70 Whitehall, adjacent to Downing Street.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The building connects three historically distinct properties, as well as the remains of Henry VIII's 1530 tennis courts, part of the Palace of Whitehall, which can be seen within the building.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The Whitehall frontage was designed by Sir John Soane and completed by Sir Charles Barry between 1845 and 1847 as the Treasury Buildings.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] Immediately to the west Dorset House (1700) connects the front of the building to William Kent's Treasury (1733–36), which faces out onto Horse Guards Parade.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The latter is built over the site of the Cockpit, used for cock fighting in the Tudor period, and subsequently as a theatre.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] In the early 1960s, the buildings were restored and many of the Tudor remains were exposed and repaired.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] Significant renovations between 2010 and 2016 converted many of the floors to open plan and created new office space.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms are located on this site.
[src:regius-professor/cabinet-office] The department occupies other buildings in Whitehall and the surrounding area, including part of the Government Offices Great George Street at 1 Horse Guards, as well as sites in other parts of the country.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In Western civilization, the study of the ancient Greek and Roman classics was considered the foundation of the humanities, and they traditionally have been the cornerstone of an elite higher education.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The word *classics* is derived from the Latin adjective *classicus*, meaning "belonging to the highest class of citizens." The word was originally used to describe the members of the Patricians, the highest class in ancient Rome.
[src:regius-professor/classics] By the 2nd century AD the word was used in literary criticism to describe writers of the highest quality.
[src:regius-professor/classics] For example, Aulus Gellius, in his *Attic Nights*, contrasts "classicus" and "proletarius" writers.
[src:regius-professor/classics] By the 6th century AD, the word had acquired a second meaning, referring to pupils at a school.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Thus, the two modern meanings of the word, referring both to literature considered to be of the highest quality and the standard texts used as part of a curriculum, were both derived from Roman use.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In the Middle Ages, classics and education were tightly intertwined; according to Jan Ziolkowski, there is no era in history in which the link was tighter.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Medieval education taught students to imitate earlier classical models, and Latin continued to be the language of scholarship and culture, despite the increasing difference between literary Latin and the vernacular languages of Europe during the period.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The works of even major Greek authors such as Hesiod, whose names continued to be known by educated Europeans, along with most of Plato, were unavailable in Christian Europe.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Some were rediscovered through Arabic translations; a School of Translators was set up in the border city of Toledo, Spain, to translate from Arabic into Latin.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Along with the unavailability of Greek authors, there were other differences between the classical canon known today and the works valued in the Middle Ages.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Catullus, for instance, was almost entirely unknown in the medieval period.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The popularity of different authors also waxed and waned throughout the period: Lucretius, popular during the Carolingian Renaissance, was barely read in the twelfth century, while for Quintilian the reverse is true.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The Renaissance led to the increasing study of both ancient literature and ancient history, as well as a revival of classical styles of Latin.
[src:regius-professor/classics] From the 14th century, first in Italy and then increasingly across Europe, Renaissance Humanism, an intellectual movement that "advocated the study and imitation of classical antiquity", developed.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Humanism saw a reform in education in Europe, introducing a wider range of Latin authors as well as bringing back the study of Greek language and literature to Western Europe.
[src:regius-professor/classics] This reintroduction was initiated by Petrarch (1304–1374) and Boccaccio (1313–1375) who commissioned a Calabrian scholar to translate the Homeric poems.
[src:regius-professor/classics] This humanist educational reform spread from Italy, in Catholic countries as it was adopted by the Jesuits, and in countries that became Protestant such as England, Germany, and the Low Countries, in order to ensure that future clerics were able to study the New Testament in the original language.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The late 17th and 18th centuries are the period in Western European literary history which is most associated with the classical tradition, as writers consciously adapted classical models.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Classical models were so highly prized that the plays of William Shakespeare were rewritten along neoclassical lines, and these "improved" versions were performed throughout the 18th century.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In the United States, the nation's Founders were strongly influenced by the classics, and they looked in particular to the Roman Republic for their form of government.
[src:regius-professor/classics] From the beginning of the 18th century, the study of Greek became increasingly important relative to that of Latin.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In this period Johann Winckelmann's claims for the superiority of the Greek visual arts influenced a shift in aesthetic judgements, while in the literary sphere, G.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Lessing "returned Homer to the centre of artistic achievement".
[src:regius-professor/classics] In the United Kingdom, the study of Greek in schools began in the late 18th century.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The poet Walter Savage Landor claimed to have been one of the first English schoolboys to write in Greek during his time at Rugby School.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The 19th century saw the influence of the classical world, and the value of a classical education, decline, especially in the United States, where the subject was often criticised for its elitism.
[src:regius-professor/classics] By the 19th century, little new literature was still being written in Latin – a practice which had continued as late as the 18th century – and a command of Latin declined in importance.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Correspondingly, classical education from the 19th century onwards began to increasingly de-emphasise the importance of the ability to write and speak Latin.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In the United Kingdom this process took longer than elsewhere.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Composition continued to be the dominant classical skill in England until the 1870s, when new areas within the discipline began to increase in popularity.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In the same decade came the first challenges to the requirement of Greek at the universities of Oxford and Cambridge, though it would not be finally abolished for another 50 years.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Though the influence of classics as the dominant mode of education in Europe and North America was in decline in the 19th century, the discipline was rapidly evolving in the same period.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Classical scholarship was becoming more systematic and scientific, especially with the "new philology" created at the end of the 18th and beginning of the 19th century.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Its scope was also broadening: it was during the 19th century that ancient history and classical archaeology began to be seen as part of classics, rather than separate disciplines.
[src:regius-professor/classics] During the 20th century, the study of classics became less common.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In England, for instance, Oxford and Cambridge universities stopped requiring students to have qualifications in Greek in 1920, and in Latin at the end of the 1950s.
[src:regius-professor/classics] When the National Curriculum was introduced in England, Wales, and Northern Ireland in 1988, it did not mention the classics.
[src:regius-professor/classics] By 2003, only about 10% of state schools in Britain offered any classical subjects to their students at all.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In 2016, AQA, the largest exam board for A-Levels and GCSEs in England, Wales and Northern Ireland, announced that it would be scrapping A-Level subjects in Classical Civilisation, Archaeology, and Art History.
[src:regius-professor/classics] This left just one out of five exam boards in England which still offered Classical Civilisation as a subject.
[src:regius-professor/classics] However, the study of classics has not declined as fast elsewhere in Europe.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In 2009, a review of *Meeting the Challenge*, a collection of conference papers about the teaching of Latin in Europe, noted that though there is opposition to the teaching of Latin in Italy, it is nonetheless still compulsory in most secondary schools.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The same may also be said in the case of France or Greece.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Indeed, Ancient Greek is one of the compulsory subjects in Greek secondary education, whereas in France, Latin is one of the optional subjects that can be chosen in a majority of middle schools and high schools.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Ancient Greek is also still being taught, but not as much as Latin.
[src:regius-professor/classics] One of the most notable characteristics of the modern study of classics is the diversity of the field.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Although traditionally focused on ancient Greece and Rome, the study now encompasses the entire ancient Mediterranean world, thus expanding the studies to Northern Africa and parts of the Middle East.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Philology is the study of language preserved in written sources; **classical philology** is thus concerned with understanding any texts from the classical period written in the classical languages of Latin and Greek.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The roots of classical philology lie in the Renaissance, as humanist intellectuals attempted to return to the Latin of the classical period, especially of Cicero, and as scholars attempted to produce more accurate editions of ancient texts.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Other philological tools took longer to be developed: the first statement, for instance, of the principle that a more difficult reading should be preferred over a simpler one, was in 1697 by Jean Le Clerc.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The modern discipline of classical philology began in Germany at the turn of the nineteenth century.
[src:regius-professor/classics] It was during this period that scientific principles of philology began to be put together into a coherent whole, in order to provide a set of rules by which scholars could determine which manuscripts were most accurate.
[src:regius-professor/classics] This "new philology", as it was known, centered around the construction of a genealogy of manuscripts, with which a hypothetical common ancestor, closer to the original text than any existing manuscript, could be reconstructed.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Classical archaeology is the oldest branch of archaeology, with its roots going back to J.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Winckelmann's work on Herculaneum in the 1760s.
[src:regius-professor/classics] It was not until the last decades of the 19th century, however, that classical archaeology became part of the tradition of Western classical scholarship.
[src:regius-professor/classics] It was included as part of Cambridge University's Classical Tripos for the first time after the reforms of the 1880s, though it did not become part of Oxford's Greats until much later.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The second half of the 19th century saw Schliemann's excavations of Troy and Mycenae; the first excavations at Olympia and Delos; and Arthur Evans' work in Crete, particularly on Knossos.
[src:regius-professor/classics] More recently, classical archaeology has taken little part in the theoretical changes in the rest of the discipline, largely ignoring the popularity of "New Archaeology", which emphasized the development of general laws derived from studying material culture, in the 1960s.
[src:regius-professor/classics] New Archaeology is still criticized by traditional minded scholars of classical archaeology despite a wide acceptance of its basic techniques.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Some art historians focus their study on the development of art in the classical world.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Indeed, the art and architecture of ancient Rome and Greece is very well regarded and remains at the heart of much of our art today.
[src:regius-professor/classics] For example, ancient Greek architecture gave us the classical orders: Doric, Ionic, and Corinthian.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The Parthenon is still the architectural symbol of the classical world.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Greek sculpture is well known and we know the names of several ancient Greek artists: for example, Phidias.
[src:regius-professor/classics] With philology, archaeology, and art history, scholars seek understanding of the history and culture of a civilization, through critical study of the extant literary and physical artefacts, in order to compose and establish a continual historic narrative of the Ancient World and its peoples.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The English word *philosophy* comes from the Greek word φιλοσοφία, meaning "love of wisdom", probably coined by Pythagoras.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Along with the word itself, the discipline of philosophy as we know it today has its roots in ancient Greek thought, and according to Martin West "philosophy as we understand it is a Greek creation".
[src:regius-professor/classics] Ancient philosophy was traditionally divided into three branches: logic, physics, and ethics.
[src:regius-professor/classics] However, not all of the works of ancient philosophers fit neatly into one of these three branches.
[src:regius-professor/classics] For instance, Aristotle's *Rhetoric* and *Poetics* have been traditionally classified in the West as "ethics", but in the Arabic world were grouped with logic; in reality, they do not fit neatly into either category.
[src:regius-professor/classics] From the last decade of the eighteenth century, scholars of ancient philosophy began to study the discipline historically.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Previously, works on ancient philosophy had been unconcerned with chronological sequence and with reconstructing the reasoning of ancient thinkers; with what Wolfgang-Ranier Mann calls "New Philosophy", this changed.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Another discipline within the classics is "reception studies", which developed in the 1960s at the University of Konstanz.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Reception studies is concerned with how students of classical texts have understood and interpreted them.
[src:regius-professor/classics] As such, reception studies is interested in a two-way interaction between reader and text, taking place within a historical context.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Though the idea of an "aesthetics of reception" was first put forward by Hans Robert Jauss in 1967, the principles of reception theory go back much earlier than this.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Eliot wrote that "the past [is] altered by the present as much as the present is directed by the past"; Charles Martindale describes this as a "cardinal principle" for many versions of modern reception theory.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Ancient Greece was the civilization belonging to the period of Greek history lasting from the Archaic period, beginning in the eighth century BC, to the Roman conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The Classical period, during the fifth and fourth centuries BC, has traditionally been considered the height of Greek civilisation.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The Classical period of Greek history is generally considered to have begun with the first and second Persian invasions of Greece at the start of the Greco-Persian wars, and to have ended with the death of Alexander the Great.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Classical Greek culture had a powerful influence on the Roman Empire, which carried a version of it to many parts of the Mediterranean region and Europe; thus Classical Greece is generally considered to be the seminal culture which provided the foundation of Western civilization.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Ancient Greek is the historical stage in the development of the Greek language spanning the Archaic (c.
[src:regius-professor/classics] 5th to 4th centuries BC), and Hellenistic (c.
[src:regius-professor/classics] 3rd century BC to 6th century AD) periods of ancient Greece and the ancient world.
[src:regius-professor/classics] It is predated in the 2nd millennium BC by Mycenaean Greek.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Its Hellenistic phase is known as Koine ("common") or Biblical Greek, and its late period mutates imperceptibly into Medieval Greek.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Koine is regarded as a separate historical stage of its own, although in its earlier form it closely resembles Classical Greek.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Prior to the Koine period, Greek of the classical and earlier periods included several regional dialects.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of classical Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:regius-professor/classics] It has contributed many words to the vocabulary of English and many other European languages, and has been a standard subject of study in Western educational institutions since the Renaissance.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Latinized forms of Ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in other scientific terminology.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The earliest surviving works of Greek literature are epic poetry.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Homer's *Iliad* and *Odyssey* are the earliest to survive to us today, probably composed in the eighth century BC.
[src:regius-professor/classics] These early epics were oral compositions, created without the use of writing.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Around the same time that the Homeric epics were composed, the Greek alphabet was introduced; the earliest surviving inscriptions date from around 750 BC.
[src:regius-professor/classics] European drama was invented in ancient Greece.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Traditionally this was attributed to Thespis, around the middle of the sixth century BC, though the earliest surviving work of Greek drama is Aeschylus' tragedy *The Persians*, which dates to 472 BC.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Early Greek tragedy was performed by a chorus and two actors, but by the end of Aeschylus' life, a third actor had been introduced, either by him or by Sophocles.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The last surviving Greek tragedies are the *Bacchae* of Euripides and Sophocles' Oedipus at Colonus, both from the end of the fifth century BC.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Surviving Greek comedy begins later than tragedy; the earliest surviving work, Aristophanes' *Acharnians*, comes from 425 BC.
[src:regius-professor/classics] However, comedy dates back as early as 486 BC, when the Dionysia added a competition for comedy to the much earlier competition for tragedy.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The comedy of the fifth century is known as Old Comedy, and it comes down to us solely in the eleven surviving plays of Aristophanes, along with a few fragments.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Sixty years after the end of Aristophanes' career, the next author of comedies to have any substantial body of work survive is Menander, whose style is known as New Comedy.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Greek mythology is the body of myths and legends belonging to the ancient Greeks concerning their gods and heroes, the nature of the world, and the origins and significance of their own cult and ritual practices.
[src:regius-professor/classics] They were a part of religion in ancient Greece.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Modern scholars refer to the myths and study them in an attempt to throw light on the religious and political institutions of ancient Greece and its civilization, and to gain understanding of the nature of myth-making itself.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Greek religion encompassed the collection of beliefs and rituals practiced in ancient Greece in the form of both popular public religion and cult practices.
[src:regius-professor/classics] These different groups varied enough for it to be possible to speak of Greek religions or "cults" in the plural, though most of them shared similarities.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Also, the Greek religion extended out of Greece and out to neighbouring islands.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Different cities often worshipped the same deities, sometimes with epithets that distinguished them and specified their local nature.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The earliest surviving philosophy from ancient Greece dates back to the 6th century BC, when according to Aristotle Thales of Miletus was considered to have been the first Greek philosopher.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Other influential pre-Socratic philosophers include Pythagoras and Heraclitus.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The most famous and significant figures in classical Athenian philosophy, from the 5th to the 3rd centuries BC, are Socrates, his student Plato, and Aristotle, who studied at Plato's Academy before founding his own school, known as the Lyceum.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Later Greek schools of philosophy, including the Cynics, Stoics, and Epicureans, continued to be influential after the Roman annexation of Greece, and into the post-Classical world.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Greek philosophy dealt with a wide variety of subjects, including political philosophy, ethics, metaphysics, ontology, and logic, as well as disciplines which are not today thought of as part of philosophy, such as biology and rhetoric.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The language of ancient Rome was Latin, a member of the Italic family of languages.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The earliest surviving inscription in Latin comes from the 7th century BC, on a brooch from Palestrina.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Latin from between this point and the early 1st century BC is known as Old Latin.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Most surviving Latin literature is Classical Latin, from the 1st century BC to the 2nd century AD.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Latin then evolved into Late Latin, in use during the late antique period.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Late Latin survived long after the end of classical antiquity, and was finally replaced by written Romance languages around the 9th century AD.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Along with literary forms of Latin, there existed various vernacular dialects, generally known as Vulgar Latin, in use throughout antiquity.
[src:regius-professor/classics] These are mainly preserved in sources such as graffiti and the Vindolanda tablets.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Latin literature seems to have started in 240 BC, when a Roman audience saw a play adapted from the Greek by Livius Andronicus.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Andronicus also translated Homer's *Odyssey* into Saturnian verse.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The poets Ennius, Accius, and Patruvius followed.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Their work survives only in fragments; the earliest Latin authors whose work we have full examples of are the playwrights Plautus and Terence.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Much of the best known and most highly thought of Latin literature comes from the classical period, with poets such as Virgil, Horace, and Ovid; historians such as Julius Caesar and Tacitus; orators such as Cicero; and philosophers such as Seneca the Younger and Lucretius.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Late Latin authors include many Christian writers such as Lactantius, Tertullian and Ambrose; non-Christian authors, such as the historian Ammianus Marcellinus, are also preserved.
[src:regius-professor/classics] According to legend, the city of Rome was founded in 753 BC; in reality, there had been a settlement on the site since around 1000 BC, when the Palatine Hill was settled.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The city was originally ruled by kings, first Roman, and then Etruscan – according to Roman tradition, the first Etruscan king of Rome, Tarquinius Priscus, ruled from 616 BC.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Over the course of the 6th century BC, the city expanded its influence over the entirety of Latium.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Around the end of the 6th century – traditionally in 510 BC – the kings of Rome were driven out, and the city became a republic.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Around 387 BC, Rome was sacked by the Gauls following the Battle of the Allia.
[src:regius-professor/classics] It soon recovered from this humiliating defeat, however, and in 381 the inhabitants of Tusculum in Latium were made Roman citizens.
[src:regius-professor/classics] This was the first time Roman citizenship was extended in this way.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Rome went on to expand its area of influence, until by 269 the entirety of the Italian peninsula was under Roman rule.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Soon afterwards, in 264, the First Punic War began; it lasted until 241.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The Second Punic War began in 218, and by the end of that year, the Carthaginian general Hannibal had invaded Italy.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The war saw Rome's worst defeat to that point at Cannae; the largest army Rome had yet put into the field was wiped out, and one of the two consuls leading it was killed.
[src:regius-professor/classics] However, Rome continued to fight, annexing much of Spain and eventually defeating Carthage, ending her position as a major power and securing Roman preeminence in the Western Mediterranean.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The classical languages of the ancient Mediterranean world influenced every European language, imparting to each a learned vocabulary of international application.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Thus, Latin grew from a highly developed cultural product of the Golden and Silver eras of Latin literature to become the *international lingua franca* in matters diplomatic, scientific, philosophic and religious, until the 17th century.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Long before this, Latin had evolved into the Romance languages and Ancient Greek into Modern Greek and its dialects.
[src:regius-professor/classics] In the specialised science and technology vocabularies, the influence of Latin and Greek is notable.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Ecclesiastical Latin, the Roman Catholic Church's official language, remains a living legacy of the classical world in the contemporary world.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Latin had an impact far beyond the classical world.
[src:regius-professor/classics] It continued to be the pre-eminent language for serious writings in Europe long after the fall of the Roman Empire.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The modern Romance languages (French, Italian, Portuguese, Romanian, Spanish, Galician, Catalan) all derive from Latin.
[src:regius-professor/classics] Latin is still seen as a foundational aspect of European culture.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The legacy of the classical world is not confined to the influence of classical languages.
[src:regius-professor/classics] The Roman Empire was taken as a model by later European empires, such as the Spanish, French and British empires.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth was born in Mayfair, London, during the reign of her paternal grandfather, King George V.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was the first child of the Duke and Duchess of York (later King George VI and Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother).
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Her father acceded to the throne in 1936 upon the abdication of his brother Edward VIII, making the ten-year-old Princess Elizabeth the heir presumptive.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was educated privately at home and began to undertake public duties during the Second World War, serving in the Auxiliary Territorial Service.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In November 1947, she married Philip Mountbatten, a former prince of Greece and Denmark.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] They had four children: Charles, Anne, Andrew, and Edward.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] When her father died in February 1952, Elizabeth, then 25 years old, became queen of seven independent Commonwealth countries and head of the Commonwealth.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She reigned as a constitutional monarch through times of significant political change such as the Troubles in Northern Ireland, devolution in the United Kingdom, the decolonisation of Africa, and the United Kingdom's accession to the European Communities as well as its subsequent withdrawal.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The number of her realms varied over time as territories gained independence and as most realms became republics.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As queen, Elizabeth was advised by more than 170 prime ministers across her realms.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Her many historic visits and meetings included state visits to China in 1986, to Russia in 1994, and to the Republic of Ireland in 2011; she met five popes and fourteen US presidents.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Significant events of Elizabeth's reign included her coronation in 1953 and the celebrations of her Silver, Golden, Diamond, and Platinum jubilees.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth died aged 96 at Balmoral Castle in Scotland, and was succeeded by her eldest son, Charles III.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth was born at 2:40 am on 21 April 1926 by Caesarean section at her maternal grandfather's London home, 17 Bruton Street in Mayfair, the first child of Prince Albert, Duke of York (later King George VI), and his wife, Elizabeth, Duchess of York (later Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother).
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Her father was the second son of King George V and Queen Mary, and her mother was the youngest daughter of Scottish aristocrat Claude Bowes-Lyon, 14th Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne, and his wife Cecilia (née Cavendish-Bentinck).
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was baptised in the private chapel at Buckingham Palace on 29 May by the Archbishop of York, Cosmo Gordon Lang, and was named Elizabeth after her mother; Alexandra after her paternal great-grandmother, who had died five months earlier; and Mary after her paternal grandmother.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Her close family affectionately called her "Lilibet", based on what she called herself at first.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was cherished by her grandfather George V, whom she affectionately called "Grandpa England", and her regular visits during his serious illness in 1929 were credited in the popular press and by later biographers with raising his spirits and aiding his recovery.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's sole sibling, Princess Margaret, was born in 1930.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] They were cared for by their nanny, Clara Knight, and educated at home under the supervision of their mother and their governess, Marion Crawford.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Lessons concentrated on history, language, literature, and music.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Crawford published a biography of Elizabeth and Margaret's childhood years titled *The Little Princesses* in 1950, much to the dismay of the royal family.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The book describes Elizabeth's love of horses and dogs, her orderliness, and her attitude of responsibility.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Others echoed such observations: Winston Churchill described Elizabeth when she was two as "a character.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She has an air of authority and reflectiveness astonishing in an infant." Her cousin Margaret Rhodes described her as "a jolly little girl, but fundamentally sensible and well-behaved".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's early life was spent primarily at the Yorks' residences at 145 Piccadilly (their town house in London) and Royal Lodge in Windsor.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] During her grandfather's reign, Elizabeth was third in the line of succession to the British throne, behind her uncle Edward, Prince of Wales, and her father.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Although her birth generated public interest, she was not expected to become queen, as Edward was still young and expected to marry and have children of his own, who would precede Elizabeth in the line of succession.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] When her grandfather died in 1936 and her uncle succeeded as Edward VIII, she became second in line to the throne, after her father.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Later that year, Edward abdicated, after his proposed marriage to divorced American socialite Wallis Simpson provoked a constitutional crisis.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Consequently, Elizabeth's father became king, taking the regnal name George VI.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Since Elizabeth had no brothers, she became heir presumptive.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] If her parents had subsequently had a son, he would have been heir apparent and before her in the line of succession, which was determined by the male-preference primogeniture in effect at the time.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth received private tuition in constitutional history from Henry Marten, Vice-Provost of Eton College, and learned French from a succession of native-speaking governesses.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] A Girl Guides company, the 1st Buckingham Palace Company, was formed specifically so she could socialise with girls her age.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Later, she was enrolled as a Sea Ranger.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1939, Elizabeth's parents toured Canada and the United States.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As in 1927, when they had toured Australia and New Zealand, Elizabeth remained in Britain since her father thought she was too young to undertake public tours.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She "looked tearful" as her parents departed.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] They corresponded regularly, and she and her parents made the first royal transatlantic telephone call on 18 May.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In September 1939, Britain entered the Second World War.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Lord Hailsham suggested that Elizabeth and Margaret should be evacuated to Canada to avoid the frequent aerial bombings of London by the *Luftwaffe*.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] This was rejected by their mother, who declared, "The children won't go without me.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] And the King will never leave." The princesses stayed at Balmoral Castle, Scotland, until Christmas 1939, when they moved to Sandringham House, Norfolk.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] From February to May 1940, they lived at Royal Lodge, Windsor, until moving to Windsor Castle, where they lived for most of the next five years.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] At Windsor, the princesses staged pantomimes at Christmas in aid of the Queen's Wool Fund, which bought yarn to knit into military garments.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1940, the 14-year-old Elizabeth made her first radio broadcast during the BBC's *Children's Hour*, addressing other children who had been evacuated from the cities.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She stated: "We are trying to do all we can to help our gallant sailors, soldiers, and airmen, and we are trying, too, to bear our own share of the danger and sadness of war.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1943, Elizabeth undertook her first solo public appearance on a visit to the Grenadier Guards, of which she had been appointed colonel the previous year.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As she approached her 18th birthday, Parliament changed the law so that she could act as one of five counsellors of state in the event of her father's incapacity or absence abroad, such as his visit to Italy in July 1944.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In February 1945, she was appointed an honorary second subaltern in the Auxiliary Territorial Service with the service number 230873.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She trained as a driver and mechanic and was given the rank of honorary junior commander (female equivalent of captain at the time) five months later.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] At the end of the war in Europe, on Victory in Europe Day, Elizabeth and Margaret mingled incognito with the celebrating crowds in the streets of London.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1985, Elizabeth recalled in a rare interview, "... we asked my parents if we could go out and see for ourselves.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] I remember we were terrified of being recognised ...
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] During the war, plans were drawn to quell Welsh nationalism by affiliating Elizabeth more closely with Wales.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Proposals, such as appointing her Constable of Caernarfon Castle or a patron of Urdd Gobaith Cymru (the Welsh League of Youth), were abandoned for several reasons, including fear of associating Elizabeth with conscientious objectors in the Urdd at a time when Britain was at war.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Welsh politicians suggested she be made Princess of Wales on her 18th birthday.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Home Secretary Herbert Morrison supported the idea, but the King rejected it because he felt such a title belonged solely to the wife of a prince of Wales and the prince of Wales had always been the heir apparent.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1946, she was inducted into the Gorsedd of Bards at the National Eisteddfod of Wales.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth went on her first overseas tour in 1947, accompanying her parents through southern Africa.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth met her future husband, Prince Philip of Greece and Denmark, in 1934 and again in 1937.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] They were second cousins once removed through King Christian IX of Denmark and third cousins through Queen Victoria.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] After meeting for the third time at the Royal Naval College in Dartmouth in July 1939, Elizabeth – though only 13 years old – said she fell in love with Philip, who was 18, and they began to exchange letters.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was 21 when their engagement was officially announced on 9 July 1947.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The engagement attracted some controversy.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Philip had no financial standing, was foreign-born (though a British subject who had served in the Royal Navy throughout the Second World War), and his sisters had married German noblemen with Nazi links.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Marion Crawford wrote, "Some of the King's advisors did not think him good enough for her.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] He was a prince without a home or kingdom.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Some of the papers played long and loud tunes on the string of Philip's foreign origin." Later biographies reported that Elizabeth's mother had reservations about the union initially and teased Philip as "the Hun".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In later life, however, she told the biographer Tim Heald that Philip was "an English gentleman".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Before the marriage, Philip renounced his Greek and Danish titles, officially converted from Greek Orthodoxy to Anglicanism, and adopted the style *Lieutenant Philip Mountbatten*, taking the surname of his mother's British family.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Shortly before the wedding, he was created Duke of Edinburgh and granted the style *His Royal Highness*.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth and Philip were married on 20 November 1947 at Westminster Abbey.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] They received 2,500 wedding gifts from around the world.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth required ration coupons to buy the material for her gown (which was designed by Norman Hartnell) because Britain had not yet completely recovered from the devastation of the war.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In post-war Britain, it was not acceptable for Philip's German relations, including his three surviving sisters, to be invited to the wedding.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Neither was an invitation extended to the Duke of Windsor, formerly King Edward VIII.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth gave birth to her first child, Prince Charles, in November 1948.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] One month earlier, the King had issued letters patent allowing her children to use the style and title of a royal prince or princess, to which they otherwise would not have been entitled, as their father was no longer a royal prince.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] A second child, Princess Anne, was born in August 1950.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Following their wedding, the couple leased Windlesham Moor, near Windsor Castle, until July 1949, when they took up residence at Clarence House in London.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] At various times between 1949 and 1951, Philip was stationed in the British Crown Colony of Malta as a serving Royal Navy officer.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] He and Elizabeth lived intermittently in Malta for several months at a time in the hamlet of Gwardamanġa, at Villa Guardamangia, the rented home of Philip's uncle Lord Mountbatten.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As George VI's health declined during 1951, Elizabeth frequently stood in for him at public events.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Truman in Washington, DC, in October 1951, her private secretary Martin Charteris carried a draft accession declaration in case the King died while she was on tour.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In early 1952, Elizabeth and Philip set out for a tour of Australia and New Zealand by way of the British colony of Kenya.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 6 February, they had just returned to their Kenyan home, Sagana Lodge, after a night spent at Treetops Hotel, when word arrived of the death of Elizabeth's father.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She chose to retain Elizabeth as her regnal name, and was therefore called Elizabeth II.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The numeral offended some Scots, as she was the first Elizabeth to rule in Scotland.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was proclaimed queen throughout her realms, and the royal party hastily returned to the United Kingdom.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth and Philip moved into Buckingham Palace.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] With Elizabeth's accession, it seemed possible that the royal house would take her husband's name, in line with the custom for married women of the time.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Lord Mountbatten advocated for *House of Mountbatten*, and Philip suggested *House of Edinburgh*, after his ducal title.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The British prime minister, Winston Churchill, and Elizabeth's grandmother Queen Mary favoured the retention of the House of Windsor.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth issued a declaration on 9 April 1952 that the royal house would continue to be *Windsor*.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Philip complained, "I am the only man in the country not allowed to give his name to his own children." In 1960, the surname *Mountbatten-Windsor* was adopted for Philip and Elizabeth's male-line descendants who do not carry royal titles.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Amid preparations for the coronation, Margaret told her sister she wished to marry Peter Townsend, a divorcé 16 years Margaret's senior with two sons from his previous marriage.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] If Margaret had contracted a civil marriage, she would have been expected to renounce her right of succession.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Margaret decided to abandon her plans with Townsend.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1960, she married Antony Armstrong-Jones, who was created Earl of Snowdon the following year.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] They divorced in 1978; Margaret did not remarry.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Despite Queen Mary's death on 24 March 1953, the coronation went ahead on 2 June, as originally scheduled, as Mary had requested.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The coronation ceremony in Westminster Abbey was televised for the first time, with the exception of the anointing and communion.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On Elizabeth's instruction, her coronation gown was embroidered with the floral emblems of Commonwealth countries.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] From Elizabeth's birth onwards, the British Empire continued its transformation into the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] By the time of her accession in 1952, the monarch's role as head of multiple independent states was already established.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1953, Elizabeth and Philip embarked on a seven-month round-the-world tour, visiting 13 countries and covering more than 40,000 miles (64,000 km) by land, sea and air.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She became the first reigning monarch of Australia and New Zealand to visit those nations.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] During the tour, crowds were immense; three-quarters of the population of Australia were estimated to have seen her.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Throughout her reign, she made hundreds of state visits to other countries and tours of the Commonwealth; she was the most widely travelled head of state.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] During the run-up to the Suez Crisis in 1956, the British and French prime ministers, Sir Anthony Eden and Guy Mollet, secretly discussed the possibility of France joining the Commonwealth.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] But Mollet's proposal was not accepted, and the following year, France signed the Treaty of Rome, which established the European Economic Community, the precursor to the European Union.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In November 1956, Britain and France invaded Egypt in an ultimately unsuccessful attempt to capture the Suez Canal.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Lord Mountbatten said that Elizabeth was opposed to the invasion, though Eden denied it.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The governing Conservative Party had no formal mechanism for choosing a leader, meaning that it fell to Elizabeth to decide whom to commission to form a government following Eden's resignation.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Eden recommended she consult Lord Salisbury, the lord president of the council.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Lord Salisbury and Lord Kilmuir, the lord chancellor, consulted the British Cabinet, Churchill, and the chairman of the backbench 1922 Committee, resulting in Elizabeth appointing their recommended candidate: Harold Macmillan.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The Suez crisis and the choice of Eden's successor led, in 1957, to the first major personal criticism of Elizabeth.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In a magazine, which he owned and edited, Lord Altrincham accused her of being "out of touch".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Altrincham was denounced by public figures and slapped by a member of the public appalled by his comments.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Six years later, in 1963, Macmillan resigned and advised Elizabeth to appoint Alec Douglas-Home as the prime minister, advice she followed.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth again came under criticism for appointing the prime minister on the advice of a small number of ministers or a single minister.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1965, the Conservatives adopted a formal mechanism for electing a leader, thus relieving Elizabeth of her involvement.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1957, Elizabeth made a state visit to the United States, where she addressed the United Nations General Assembly on behalf of the Commonwealth.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On the same tour, she opened the 23rd Canadian Parliament, becoming the first monarch of Canada to open a parliamentary session.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Two years later, solely in her capacity as Queen of Canada, she revisited the United States and toured Canada.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1961, she toured Cyprus, India, Pakistan, Nepal, and Iran.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On a visit to Ghana the same year, she dismissed fears for her safety, even though her host, President Kwame Nkrumah, who had replaced her as head of state, was a target for assassins.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Harold Macmillan wrote, "The Queen has been absolutely determined all through ...
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She is impatient of the attitude towards her to treat her as ... a film star ...
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She has indeed 'the heart and stomach of a man' ...
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She loves her duty and means to be a Queen." Before her tour through parts of Quebec in 1964, the press reported that extremists within the Quebec separatist movement were plotting Elizabeth's assassination.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] No assassination attempt was made, but a riot did break out while she was in Montreal; her "calmness and courage in the face of the violence" was noted.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth gave birth to her third child, Andrew, in February 1960; this was the first birth to a reigning British monarch since 1857.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Her fourth child, Prince Edward, was born in March 1964.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] According to biographer Gyles Brandreth, Elizabeth suffered a miscarriage at some point during her reign.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The 1960s and 1970s saw an acceleration in the decolonisation of Africa and the Caribbean.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] More than 20 countries gained independence from Britain as part of a planned transition to self-government.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1965, however, the Rhodesian prime minister, Ian Smith, in opposition to moves towards majority rule, unilaterally declared independence with Elizabeth as "Queen of Rhodesia".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Although Elizabeth formally dismissed him, and the international community applied sanctions against Rhodesia, his regime survived for over a decade.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As Britain's ties to its former empire weakened, the British government sought entry to the European Community, a goal it achieved in 1973.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1966, Elizabeth was criticised for waiting eight days before visiting the village of Aberfan, where a mining disaster killed 116 children and 28 adults.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Martin Charteris said that the delay, made on his advice, was a mistake that she later regretted.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth toured Yugoslavia in October 1972, becoming the first British monarch to visit a communist country.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was received at the airport by President Josip Broz Tito, and a crowd of thousands greeted her in Belgrade.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In February 1974, British prime minister Edward Heath advised Elizabeth to call a general election in the middle of her tour of the Austronesian Pacific Rim, requiring her to fly back to Britain.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The election resulted in a hung parliament; Heath's Conservatives were not the largest party but could stay in office if they formed a coalition with the Liberals.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] When discussions on forming a coalition foundered, Heath resigned, and Elizabeth asked the Leader of the Opposition, Labour's Harold Wilson, to form a government.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] A year later, at the height of the 1975 Australian constitutional crisis, the Australian prime minister, Gough Whitlam, was dismissed from his post by Governor-General Sir John Kerr, after the Opposition-controlled Senate rejected Whitlam's budget proposals.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As Whitlam had a majority in the House of Representatives, Speaker Gordon Scholes appealed to Elizabeth to reverse Kerr's decision.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She declined, saying she would not interfere in decisions reserved by the Constitution of Australia for the governor-general.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The crisis fuelled Australian republicanism.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1977, Elizabeth marked the Silver Jubilee of her accession.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Parties and events took place throughout the Commonwealth, many coinciding with her associated national and Commonwealth tours.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The celebrations re-affirmed Elizabeth's popularity, despite virtually coincident negative press coverage of Margaret's separation from her husband, Lord Snowdon.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1978, Elizabeth endured a state visit to the United Kingdom by Romania's communist leader, Nicolae Ceaușescu, and his wife, Elena, though privately she thought they had "blood on their hands".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The following year brought two blows: the unmasking of Anthony Blunt, former Surveyor of the Queen's Pictures, as a communist spy and the assassination of Lord Mountbatten by the Provisional Irish Republican Army.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] According to Paul Martin Sr., by the end of the 1970s, Elizabeth was worried the Crown "had little meaning for" Pierre Trudeau, the Canadian prime minister.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Tony Benn said Elizabeth found Trudeau "rather disappointing".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Trudeau's supposed republicanism seemed to be confirmed by his antics, such as sliding down banisters at Buckingham Palace and pirouetting behind Elizabeth's back in 1977, and the removal of various Canadian royal symbols during his term of office.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1980, Canadian politicians sent to London to discuss the patriation of the Canadian constitution found Elizabeth "better informed ... than any of the British politicians or bureaucrats".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was particularly interested after the failure of Bill C-60, which would have affected her role as head of state.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] During the 1981 Trooping the Colour ceremony, six weeks before the wedding of Prince Charles and Lady Diana Spencer, six shots were fired at Elizabeth from close range as she rode down The Mall, London, on her horse, Burmese.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Police later discovered the shots were blanks.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The 17-year-old assailant, Marcus Sarjeant, was sentenced to five years in prison and released after three.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's composure and skill in controlling her mount were widely praised.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] That October, Elizabeth was the subject of another attack while on a visit to Dunedin, New Zealand.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Christopher John Lewis, who was 17 years old, fired a shot with a .22 rifle from the fifth floor of a building overlooking the parade but missed.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Lewis was arrested, but instead of being charged with attempted murder or treason was sentenced to three years in jail for unlawful possession and discharge of a firearm.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Two years into his sentence, he attempted to escape a psychiatric hospital with the intention of assassinating Charles, who was visiting the country with Diana and their son Prince William.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] From April to September 1982, Elizabeth's son Andrew served with British forces in the Falklands War, for which she reportedly felt anxiety and pride.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 9 July, she awoke in her bedroom at Buckingham Palace to find an intruder, Michael Fagan, in the room with her.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In a serious lapse of security, assistance only arrived after two calls to the Palace police switchboard.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] After hosting US president Ronald Reagan at Windsor Castle in 1982 and visiting his California ranch in 1983, Elizabeth was angered when his administration ordered the invasion of Grenada, one of her Caribbean realms, without informing her.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Intense media interest in the opinions and private lives of the royal family during the 1980s led to a series of sensational stories in the press, pioneered by *The Sun* tabloid.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As Kelvin MacKenzie, editor of *The Sun*, told his staff: "Give me a Sunday for Monday splash on the Royals.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The sources of the rumours included royal aide Michael Shea and Commonwealth secretary-general Shridath Ramphal, but Shea claimed his remarks were taken out of context and embellished by speculation.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Thatcher reputedly said Elizabeth would vote for the Social Democratic Party – Thatcher's political opponents.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Thatcher's biographer John Campbell claimed "the report was a piece of journalistic mischief-making".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Reports of acrimony between them were exaggerated, and Elizabeth gave two honours in her personal gift – membership in the Order of Merit and the Order of the Garter – to Thatcher after her replacement as prime minister by John Major.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Brian Mulroney, Canadian prime minister between 1984 and 1993, said Elizabeth was a "behind the scenes force" in ending apartheid.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1986, Elizabeth paid a six-day state visit to the People's Republic of China, becoming the first British monarch to visit the country.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The tour included the Forbidden City, the Great Wall of China, and the Terracotta Warriors.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] At a state banquet, Elizabeth joked about the first British emissary to China being lost at sea with Queen Elizabeth I's letter to the Wanli Emperor, and remarked, "fortunately postal services have improved since 1602".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's visit also signified the acceptance of both countries that sovereignty over Hong Kong would be transferred from the United Kingdom to China in 1997.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] By the end of the 1980s, Elizabeth had become the target of satire.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The involvement of younger members of the royal family in the charity game show *It's a Royal Knockout* in 1987 was ridiculed.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In Canada, Elizabeth publicly supported politically divisive constitutional amendments, prompting criticism from opponents of the proposed changes, including Pierre Trudeau.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The same year, the elected Fijian government was deposed in a military coup.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As monarch of Fiji, Elizabeth supported the attempts of Governor-General Ratu Sir Penaia Ganilau to assert executive power and negotiate a settlement.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Coup leader Sitiveni Rabuka deposed Ganilau and declared Fiji a republic.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In the wake of coalition victory in the Gulf War, Elizabeth became the first British monarch to address a joint meeting of the United States Congress in May 1991.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In November 1992, in a speech to mark the Ruby Jubilee of her accession, Elizabeth called 1992 her *annus horribilis* (a Latin phrase, meaning 'horrible year').
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Republican feeling in Britain had risen because of press estimates of Elizabeth's private wealth – contradicted by the Palace – and reports of affairs and strained marriages among her extended family.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The monarchy came under increased criticism and public scrutiny.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In an unusually personal speech, Elizabeth said that any institution must expect criticism, but suggested it might be done with "a touch of humour, gentleness and understanding".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Two days later, John Major announced plans to reform the royal finances, drawn up the previous year, including Elizabeth paying income tax from 1993 onwards, and a reduction in the civil list.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In December, Charles and his wife, Diana, formally separated.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] At the end of the year, Elizabeth sued *The Sun* newspaper for breach of copyright when it published the text of her annual Christmas message two days before it was broadcast.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The newspaper was forced to pay her legal fees and donated £200,000 to charity.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's solicitors had taken successful action against *The Sun* five years earlier for breach of copyright after it published a photograph of her daughter-in-law the Duchess of York and her granddaughter Princess Beatrice.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In January 1994, Elizabeth broke her left wrist when a horse she was riding at Sandringham tripped and fell.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In October 1994, she became the first reigning British monarch to set foot on Russian soil.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In October 1995, she was tricked into a hoax call by Montreal radio host Pierre Brassard impersonating Canadian prime minister Jean Chrétien.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth, who believed that she was speaking to Chrétien, said she supported Canadian unity and would try to influence Quebec's referendum on proposals to break away from Canada.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In the year that followed, public revelations on the state of Charles and Diana's marriage continued.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In consultation with her husband and John Major, as well as the Archbishop of Canterbury (George Carey) and her private secretary (Robert Fellowes), Elizabeth wrote to Charles and Diana at the end of December 1995, suggesting that a divorce would be advisable.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In August 1997, a year after the divorce, Diana was killed in a car crash in Paris.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth was on holiday with her extended family at Balmoral.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Diana's two sons, William and Harry, wanted to attend church, so Elizabeth and Philip took them that morning.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Afterwards, for five days, the royal couple shielded their grandsons from the intense press interest by keeping them at Balmoral where they could grieve in private, but the royal family's silence and seclusion, and the failure to fly a flag at half-mast over Buckingham Palace, caused public dismay.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Pressured by the hostile reaction, Elizabeth agreed to return to London and address the nation in a live television broadcast on 5 September, the day before Diana's funeral.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In the broadcast, she expressed admiration for Diana and her feelings "as a grandmother" for the two princes.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As a result, much of the public hostility evaporated.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In October 1997, Elizabeth and Philip made a state visit to India, which included a controversial visit to the site of the Jallianwala Bagh massacre to pay her respects.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Protesters chanted "Killer Queen, go back", and there were demands for her to apologise for the action of British troops 78 years earlier.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] At the memorial in the park, she and Philip laid a wreath and stood for a 30‑second moment of silence.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As a result, much of the fury among the public softened, and the protests were called off.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Back in London that November, the royal couple held a reception at Banqueting House to mark their golden wedding anniversary.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth made a speech and praised Philip for his role as consort, referring to him as "my strength and stay".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 1999, as part of the process of devolution in the United Kingdom, Elizabeth formally opened newly established legislatures for Wales and Scotland: the National Assembly for Wales at Cardiff in May, and the Scottish Parliament at Edinburgh in July.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On the eve of the new millennium, Elizabeth and Philip boarded a vessel from Southwark, bound for the Millennium Dome.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Before passing under Tower Bridge, she lit the National Millennium Beacon in the Pool of London using a laser torch.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Shortly before midnight, she officially opened the Dome.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] During the singing of *Auld Lang Syne*, Elizabeth held hands with Philip and British prime minister Tony Blair.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Following the 9/11 attacks in the United States, Elizabeth, breaking with tradition, ordered the American national anthem to be played during the changing of the guard at Buckingham Palace to express her solidarity with the country.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 2002, Elizabeth marked her Golden Jubilee, the 50th anniversary of her accession.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Her sister died in February and her mother in March, and the media speculated on whether the Jubilee would be a success or a failure.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Margaret's death shook Elizabeth; her funeral was one of the rare occasions where Elizabeth openly cried.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth again undertook an extensive tour of her realms, beginning in Jamaica in February, where she called the farewell banquet "memorable" after a power cut plunged King's House, the official residence of the governor-general, into darkness.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] As in 1977, there were street parties and commemorative events, and monuments were named to honour the occasion.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] One million people attended each day of the three-day main Jubilee celebration in London, and the enthusiasm shown for Elizabeth by the public was greater than many journalists had anticipated.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 2003, Elizabeth sued the *Daily Mirror* for breach of confidence and obtained an injunction which prevented the outlet from publishing information gathered by a reporter who posed as a footman at Buckingham Palace.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The newspaper also paid £25,000 towards her legal costs.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Though generally healthy throughout her life, in 2003 she had keyhole surgery on both knees.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In October 2006, she missed the opening of the new Emirates Stadium because of a strained back muscle that had been troubling her since the summer.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was, however, said to admire Blair's efforts to achieve peace in Northern Ireland.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She became the first British monarch to celebrate a diamond wedding anniversary in November 2007.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 20 March 2008, at the Church of Ireland St Patrick's Cathedral, Armagh, Elizabeth attended the first Maundy service held outside England and Wales.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth addressed the UN General Assembly for a second time in 2010, again in her capacity as Queen of all Commonwealth realms and Head of the Commonwealth.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The UN secretary-general, Ban Ki-moon, introduced her as "an anchor for our age".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] During her visit to New York, which followed a tour of Canada, she officially opened a memorial garden for British victims of the 9/11 attacks.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's 11-day visit to Australia in October 2011 was her 16th visit to the country since 1954.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] By invitation of the Irish president, Mary McAleese, she made the first state visit to the Republic of Ireland by a British monarch in May 2011.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The 2012 Diamond Jubilee marked 60 years since Elizabeth's accession, and celebrations were held throughout her realms, the wider Commonwealth, and beyond.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She and Philip undertook an extensive tour of the United Kingdom, while their children and grandchildren embarked on royal tours of other Commonwealth states on her behalf.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 4 June, Jubilee beacons were lit around the world.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 18 December, Elizabeth became the first British sovereign to attend a peacetime Cabinet meeting since George III in 1781.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth, who opened the Montreal Summer Olympics in 1976, also opened the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics in London, making her the first head of state to open two Olympic Games in two countries.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] For the London Olympics, she portrayed herself in a short film as part of the opening ceremony, alongside Daniel Craig as James Bond.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 4 April 2013, she received an honorary BAFTA award for her patronage of the film industry and was called "the most memorable Bond girl yet" at a special presentation at Windsor Castle.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In March 2013, Elizabeth stayed overnight at King Edward VII's Hospital as a precaution after developing symptoms of gastroenteritis.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] A week later, she signed the new Charter of the Commonwealth.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] That year, because of her age and the need for her to limit travelling, she chose not to attend the biennial Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting for the first time in 40 years.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was represented at the summit in Sri Lanka by Charles.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 20 April 2018, the Commonwealth heads of government announced that Charles would succeed her as Head of the Commonwealth, which the Queen stated as her "sincere wish".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She underwent cataract surgery in May 2018.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In March 2019, she gave up driving on public roads, largely as a consequence of a car accident involving her husband two months earlier.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 21 December 2007, Elizabeth surpassed her great-great-grandmother, Queen Victoria, to become the longest-lived British monarch, and she became the longest-reigning British monarch and longest-reigning queen regnant and female head of state in the world on 9 September 2015.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She became the oldest living monarch after the death of King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia on 23 January 2015.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She later became the longest-reigning current monarch and the longest-serving current head of state following the death of King Bhumibol Adulyadej of Thailand on 13 October 2016, and the oldest current head of state on the resignation of Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe on 21 November 2017.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 6 February 2017, she became the first British monarch to commemorate a sapphire jubilee, and on 20 November that year, she was the first British monarch to celebrate a platinum wedding anniversary.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Philip had retired from his official duties as Elizabeth's consort in August 2017.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 19 March 2020, as the COVID-19 pandemic hit the United Kingdom, Elizabeth moved to Windsor Castle and sequestered there as a precaution.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Public engagements were cancelled and Windsor Castle followed a strict sanitary protocol nicknamed "HMS Bubble".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In 2021, she received her first and second COVID-19 vaccinations in January and April respectively.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Philip died on 9 April 2021, after 73 years of marriage, making Elizabeth the first British monarch to reign as a widow or widower since Queen Victoria.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was reportedly at her husband's bedside when he died, and remarked in private that his death had "left a huge void".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Due to the COVID-19 restrictions in place in England at the time, Elizabeth sat alone at Philip's funeral service, which evoked sympathy from people around the world.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] It was later reported in the press that Elizabeth had rejected a government offer to relax the rules.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Despite the pandemic, Elizabeth attended the 2021 State Opening of Parliament in May, the 47th G7 summit in June, and hosted US president Joe Biden at Windsor Castle.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Biden was the 14th US president that she had met.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In October 2021, Elizabeth cancelled a planned trip to Northern Ireland and stayed overnight at King Edward VII's Hospital for "preliminary investigations".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On Christmas Day 2021, while she was staying at Windsor Castle, 19-year-old Jaswant Singh Chail broke into the gardens using a rope ladder and carrying a crossbow with the aim of assassinating Elizabeth in revenge for the Amritsar massacre.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Before he could enter any buildings, he was arrested and detained under the Mental Health Act.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In February 2023, Chail pleaded guilty to attempting to injure or alarm the sovereign, and was sentenced in October to a nine-year custodial sentence plus an additional five years on extended licence.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The sentencing judge also placed Chail under a hybrid order under section 45A of the Mental Health Act 1983, ordering that he remain at Broadmoor Hospital to be transferred into custody only after receiving psychiatric treatment.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's Platinum Jubilee celebrations began on 6 February 2022, marking 70 years since her accession.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In her accession day message, she renewed her commitment to a lifetime of public service, which she had originally made in 1947.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Later that month, Elizabeth fell ill with COVID-19 along with several family members, but she only exhibited "mild cold-like symptoms" and recovered by the end of the month.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She was present at the service of thanksgiving for her husband at Westminster Abbey on 29 March, but was unable to attend both the annual Commonwealth Day service that month and the Royal Maundy service in April, because of "episodic mobility problems".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In May, she missed the State Opening of Parliament for the first time in 59 years.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] (She did not attend the state openings in 1959 and 1963 as she was pregnant with Andrew and Edward, respectively.) Later that month she made a surprise visit to Paddington Station and officially opened the Elizabeth line, named in her honour.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth was largely confined to balcony appearances during the public jubilee celebrations, and she missed the National Service of Thanksgiving on 3 June.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 13 June, she became the second-longest reigning monarch in history (among those whose exact dates of reign are known), with 70 years and 127 days on the throne – surpassing King Bhumibol Adulyadej of Thailand.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 6 September, she appointed her 15th British prime minister, Liz Truss, at Balmoral Castle in Scotland.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] This was the only occasion on which Elizabeth received a new prime minister at a location other than Buckingham Palace.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] No other British monarch appointed as many prime ministers.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's last public message was issued on 7 September, in which she expressed her sympathy for those affected by the Saskatchewan stabbings.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth did not plan to abdicate, though she took on fewer public engagements in her later years and Charles performed more of her duties.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] She told Canadian governor-general Adrienne Clarkson in a meeting in 2002 that she would never abdicate, saying, "It is not our tradition.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 8 September 2022, Buckingham Palace stated, "Following further evaluation this morning, the Queen's doctors are concerned for Her Majesty's health and have recommended she remain under medical supervision.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The Queen remains comfortable and at Balmoral." Her immediate family rushed to Balmoral.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth died peacefully at 3:10 pm, aged 96.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Her death was announced to the public at 6:30 pm, setting in motion Operation London Bridge and, because she died in Scotland, Operation Unicorn.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth was the first monarch to die in Scotland since James V in 1542.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Her death certificate recorded her cause of death as "old age".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] According to former prime minister Boris Johnson and the biographer Gyles Brandreth, she was suffering from a form of bone marrow cancer, which Brandreth wrote was multiple myeloma.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 12 September, Elizabeth's coffin was carried up the Royal Mile in a procession to St Giles' Cathedral, where the Crown of Scotland was placed on it.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Her coffin lay at rest at the cathedral for 24 hours, guarded by the Royal Company of Archers, during which around 33,000 people filed past it.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 13 September, the coffin was flown to RAF Northolt in west London, before continuing its journey by road to Buckingham Palace.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 14 September, her coffin was taken in a military procession to Westminster Hall, where Elizabeth's body lay in state for four days.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] The coffin was guarded by members of both the Sovereign's Bodyguard and the Household Division.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] An estimated 250,000 members of the public filed past the coffin, as did politicians and other public figures.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] On 16 September, Elizabeth's children held a vigil around her coffin, and the next day her eight grandchildren did the same.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's state funeral was held at Westminster Abbey on 19 September, marking the first time a monarch's funeral service had been held there since that of George II in 1760.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] More than a million people lined the streets of central London, and the day was declared a holiday in several Commonwealth countries.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] In Windsor, a final procession involving 1,000 military personnel took place and was witnessed by 97,000 people.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] Elizabeth's fell pony and two royal corgis stood at the side of the procession.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p01] After a committal service at St George's Chapel, Windsor Castle, Elizabeth's body was interred with her husband Philip's in the King George VI Memorial Chapel later the same day, in a private ceremony attended by her closest family members.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Elizabeth rarely gave interviews, and little was known of her political opinions, which she did not express explicitly in public.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] By convention, the monarch’s political views are neither asked about nor publicly disclosed.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] When *Times* journalist Paul Routledge asked her about the miners' strike of 1984–85 during a royal tour of the newspaper's offices, she replied that it was "all about one man" (a reference to Arthur Scargill), with which Routledge disagreed.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Routledge was widely criticised in the media for asking the question and claimed that he was unaware of the protocols.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] After the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, Prime Minister David Cameron was overheard telling Mayor of New York City Michael Bloomberg that Elizabeth was pleased with the outcome, an incident for which Cameron later apologised.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] She had arguably issued a public coded statement about the referendum by telling one woman outside Balmoral Kirk that she hoped people would think "very carefully" about the outcome.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] It emerged later that Cameron had specifically requested that she register her concern.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Elizabeth had a deep sense of religious and civic duty, and took her Coronation Oath seriously.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Aside from her official religious role as supreme governor of the established Church of England, she worshipped with that church and with the national Church of Scotland.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] She demonstrated support for inter-faith relations and met with leaders of other churches and religions, including five popes: Pius XII, John XXIII, John Paul II, Benedict XVI and Francis.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] A personal note about her faith often featured in her annual Christmas Message broadcast to the Commonwealth.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Elizabeth was patron of more than 600 organisations and charities.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] The Charities Aid Foundation estimated that Elizabeth helped raise over £1.4 billion for her patronages during her reign.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Her main leisure interests included equestrianism and dogs, especially her Pembroke Welsh Corgis.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Her lifelong love of corgis began in 1933 with Dookie, the first of many royal corgis.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Scenes of a relaxed, informal home life were occasionally witnessed; she and her family, from time to time, prepared a meal together and washed the dishes afterwards.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] In the 1950s, as a young woman at the start of her reign, Elizabeth was depicted as a glamorous "fairytale Queen".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] After the trauma of the Second World War, it was a time of hope, a period of progress and achievement heralding a "new Elizabethan age".
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Lord Altrincham's accusation in 1957 that her speeches sounded like those of a "priggish schoolgirl" was an extremely rare criticism.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] In the late 1960s, attempts to portray a more modern image of the monarchy were made in the television documentary *Royal Family* and by televising Prince Charles's investiture as Prince of Wales.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Elizabeth also instituted other new practices; her first royal walkabout, meeting ordinary members of the public, took place during a tour of Australia and New Zealand in 1970.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Her wardrobe developed a recognisable, signature style driven more by function than fashion.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] In public, she took to wearing mostly solid-colour overcoats and decorative hats, allowing her to be seen easily in a crowd.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] By the end of her reign, nearly one third of Britons had seen or met Elizabeth in person.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] At Elizabeth's Silver Jubilee in 1977, the crowds and celebrations were genuinely enthusiastic; but, in the 1980s, public criticism of the royal family increased, as the personal and working lives of Elizabeth's children came under media scrutiny.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Her popularity sank to a low point in the 1990s.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Under pressure from public opinion, she began to pay income tax for the first time, and Buckingham Palace was opened to the public.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Although support for republicanism in Britain seemed higher than at any time in living memory, republican ideology was still a minority viewpoint, and Elizabeth herself had high approval ratings.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Criticism was focused on the institution of the monarchy itself, and the conduct of Elizabeth's wider family, rather than her own behaviour and actions.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Discontent with the monarchy reached its peak on the death of Diana, Princess of Wales, although Elizabeth's personal popularity – as well as general support for the monarchy – rebounded after her live television broadcast to the world five days after Diana's death.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] In November 1999, a referendum in Australia on the future of the Australian monarchy favoured its retention in preference to an indirectly elected head of state.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Many republicans credited Elizabeth's personal popularity with the survival of the monarchy in Australia.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] In 2010, Prime Minister Julia Gillard noted that there was a "deep affection" for Elizabeth in Australia and that another referendum on the monarchy should wait until after her reign.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Gillard's successor, Malcolm Turnbull, who led the republican campaign in 1999, similarly believed that Australians would not vote to become a republic in her lifetime.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] "She's been an extraordinary head of state", Turnbull said in 2021, "and I think frankly, in Australia, there are more Elizabethans than there are monarchists." Similarly, referendums in both Tuvalu in 2008 and Saint Vincent and the Grenadines in 2009 saw voters reject proposals to become republics.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Polls in Britain in 2006 and 2007 revealed strong support for the monarchy, and in 2012, Elizabeth's Diamond Jubilee year, her approval ratings hit 90 per cent.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Polling in Great Britain during the Platinum Jubilee, however, showed support for maintaining the monarchy and Elizabeth's personal popularity remained strong.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] As of 2021 she remained the third most admired woman in the world according to the annual Gallup poll, her 52 appearances on the list meaning she had been in the top ten more than any other woman in the poll's history.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Elizabeth was portrayed in a variety of media by many notable artists, including painters Pietro Annigoni, Peter Blake, Chinwe Chukwuogo-Roy, Terence Cuneo, Lucian Freud, Rolf Harris, Damien Hirst, Juliet Pannett and Tai-Shan Schierenberg.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Notable photographers of Elizabeth included Cecil Beaton, Yousuf Karsh, Anwar Hussein, Annie Leibovitz, Lord Lichfield, Terry O'Neill, John Swannell and Dorothy Wilding.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] The first official portrait photograph of Elizabeth was taken by Marcus Adams in 1926.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Elizabeth held many titles and honorary military positions throughout the Commonwealth, was sovereign of many orders in her own countries and received honours and awards from around the world.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] In each of her realms, she had a distinct title that follows a similar formula: *Queen of Saint Lucia and of Her other Realms and Territories* in Saint Lucia, *Queen of Australia and Her other Realms and Territories* in Australia, etc.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] She was also styled *Defender of the Faith*.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] From 21 April 1944 until her accession, Elizabeth's arms consisted of a lozenge bearing the royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom differenced with a label of three points argent, the centre point bearing a Tudor rose and the first and third a cross of Saint George.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Upon her accession, she inherited the various arms her father held as sovereign, with a subsequently modified representation of the crown.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Elizabeth also possessed royal standards and personal flags for use in the United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Jamaica, and elsewhere.
[src:regius-professor/elizabeth-ii-p02] Elizabeth approved her modified British arms on 26 May 1954.
[src:regius-professor/erasmus-smith-s-professor-of-hebrew] The **Erasmus Smith's Professor of Hebrew** is a professorship at Trinity College Dublin.
[src:regius-professor/erasmus-smith-s-professor-of-hebrew] A lectureship in Oriental Languages had been founded in 1637 and later endowed by Erasmus Smith's estate in 1724.
[src:regius-professor/erasmus-smith-s-professor-of-hebrew] The endowment was increased in 1762 to create a Professorship in Oriental Languages.
[src:regius-professor/erasmus-smith-s-professor-of-hebrew] The title of the chair changed to Professor of Hebrew in 1849.
[src:regius-professor/erasmus-smith-s-professor-of-hebrew] The chair was elevated to a Regius Professorship in 1855 by Royal Statute.
[src:regius-professor/erasmus-smith-s-professor-of-hebrew] However, the Board of Trinity College did not issue a decree setting out the duties or salary of the Professorship and it was presumed that the Professorship did not actually exist until called into creation by decree.
[src:regius-professor/erasmus-smith-s-professor-of-hebrew] By 1878, the Board had postponed the regular creation of the Regius Professorship and the title reverted to Erasmus Smith's Professor of Hebrew.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The ICR occupies sites in Chelsea, Central London and Sutton, southwest London.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The ICR provides both taught postgraduate degree programmes and research degrees and currently has around 340 students.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Together with the Royal Marsden Hospital the ICR forms the largest comprehensive cancer centre in Europe, and was ranked second amongst all British higher education institutions in the *Times Higher Education'*s assessment of the 2021 Research Excellence Framework.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In clinical medicine, 97% and in biological sciences, 99% of the ICR's academic research was assessed to be world leading or internationally excellent (4* or 3*).
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The annual income of the institution for 2022–23 was £138.7 million of which £64.6 million was from research grants and contracts, with an expenditure of £134.9 million.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The ICR receives its external grant funding from the government body the Higher Education Funding Council for England, from government research council bodies and from charities including the Wellcome Trust, Cancer Research UK, Breast Cancer Now and Bloodwise.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] It also receives voluntary income from legacies and from public and corporate donations.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The ICR also runs a number of fundraising appeals and campaigns which help support a variety of cancer research projects.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The ICR occupies two sites in Chelsea, Central London which include the Chester Beatty Laboratories and the ICR corporate offices.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] A third site in Sutton, Southwest London, houses more research facilities.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The location of the two research sites reflects the two sites of the Royal Marsden Hospital.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The ICR pursues its research focused into three main research themes: genetic epidemiology, molecular pathology, and therapeutic development.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] These areas of research are essential for the development of personalised cancer medicine.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Towards this aim, the ICR and The Royal Marsden have completed a dedicated £17 million Centre for Molecular Pathology (CMP) which opened on the Sutton site on 20 November 2012.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The centre exploits the increasing availability of information about the genetic make-up of different cancer types, in order to design new "personalised" treatments that target cancers' specific molecular defects.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The CMP also aims to develop molecular diagnostic techniques that will accurately predict who will benefit most from a treatment, ensuring a patient receives the optimum drug(s) for the best possible outcome.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The CMP will build on the organisations' existing expertise in breast, prostate and paediatric cancers, while providing opportunities for new developments in other cancers such as gastrointestinal, renal, gynaecological, melanoma, head & neck cancers and sarcomas.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In March 2016, the ICR opened a £20 million Centre for Cancer Imaging that brings together experts in a range of different imaging techniques working together to develop better cancer diagnostic and treatment techniques.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The organisation's research direction is set out in the ICR Scientific Strategy 2010–2015, which aims to develop key research areas while enhancing partnership affiliations.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The ICR runs an MSc in Oncology programme, which is a modular course aimed primarily at Specialist Registrars in Clinical and Medical Oncology.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The course has exit points at Certificate, Diploma and MSc degree level.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The ICR was founded in 1909, when a new laboratory building adjoining The Cancer Hospital (later named the Royal Marsden Hospital) was established with Alexander Paine as its first director.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1910 Robert Knox was appointed to head the Electrical and Radio-therapeutic Department at The Cancer Hospital and established the first professionally designed X-ray Department for treatment and diagnosis in Britain.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The Cancer Hospital Research Institute was officially opened by Prince Arthur, the Duke of Connaught, in 1911.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1921 Archibald Leitch was appointed director of The Cancer Hospital Research Institute.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The institute became a postgraduate School of the University of London in 1927.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1931 Sir Ernest Kennaway FRS became director of the institute.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1932 a research team led by Kennaway fractionated coal tar and isolated benzo[a]pyrene, which he identified as one of the chemical constituents that induced cancer in mice.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] These were the first research findings to show that a pure chemical substance can cause cancer.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1936 Kennaway proposed the potential of a link between smoking and lung cancer.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The Cancer Hospital Research Institute moved to a new site on Fulham Road in Chelsea in 1939 and was renamed the Chester Beatty Research Institute.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1946 Sir Alexander Haddow FRS FRSE (1907–1976) became the director of the Chester Beatty Research Institute.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] He remained in the role until 1969, In 1947, while conducting research at the institute, David Galton became the first physician in the world to use aminopterin (the forerunner of the methotrexate drug) in the treatment of adult leukaemia, producing remission in some cancer patients.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] During the 1940s Haddow established a Clinical Chemotherapy Research Unit – the first such unit in Europe – in partnership with the Royal Marsden Hospital and under Galton's leadership.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The partnership was unique at the time in being able to take the drug discoveries directly into a partner hospital for clinical trials in cancer patients.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The unit led to the institute's discovery of three successful chemotherapy drugs in the 1950s: busulphan (Myleran), chlorambucil (Leukeran) and melphalan (Alkeran).
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1952 the ICR's Eric Boyland had proposed that certain chemicals that cause cancer (carcinogens) react with DNA through an alkylation mechanism that damaged the DNA molecule.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In follow-up research at the ICR in 1964, Professors Peter Brookes and Philip Lawley proved that chemical carcinogens act by damaging DNA, leading to mutations and the formation of tumours, proving that cancer is a genetic disease based on mutational events.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1954 the institute was officially renamed The Institute of Cancer Research (ICR).
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The ICR established a second campus in Sutton, Surrey, in 1956.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Whilst working at the ICR in 1961, Jacques Miller discovered the immunological role of the thymus, as the repository of a special class of lymphocytes (T cells) essential for the mounting of an immune response.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Scientists at the ICR were instrumental in the development of one of the world's most widely used anti-cancer drugs, carboplatin (Paraplatin).
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Carboplatin's development began in 1970 after scientists in the United States discovered that the platinum-based compound cisplatin was effective against many tumours – but had serious side-effects.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] A team of ICR and RMH scientists and clinicians including Professors Kenneth Harrap and Tom Connors, Hilary Calvert and Hospital Consultant Eve Wiltshaw recognised its potential but also the need for a less toxic alternative.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In collaboration with the chemical and precious metal company Johnson Matthey plc the ICR scientists evaluated some 300 different platinum-containing molecules and developed a series of second-generation compounds, of which carboplatin was selected as the lead.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The first clinical trial of carboplatin was carried out in 1981 and it was launched commercially as Parplatin (manufactured by Bristol-Myers) in 1986.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] As of 2012 carboplatin is in use for a range of cancers including ovarian and lung.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] For the development of these platinum-based anticancer drugs the ICR, together with The Royal Marsden Hospital and Johnson Matthey plc, received the Queen's Award for Technological Achievement in 1991.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] During the 1980s ICR scientists including Professors Hilary Calvert, and Ken Harrap and Ann Jackman developed raltitrexed (Tomudex) at the ICR, a drug active for the treatment of colon and other cancers.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1983 research teams at the Chester Beatty Laboratory of the ICR led by Professors Chris Marshall FRS and Alan Hall FRS discovered N-RAS, one of the first human cancer transforming genes (oncogenes).
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Alan Hall went on in 1992 to discover that the molecular mechanism for the motility behaviour of animal cells (cell to cell attachment and cell movement) is through control of cytoskeletal assembly by specific GTPase-proteins, known as Rho and Rac.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The discovery is of fundamental significance in cancer research since cell motility is a key feature of cancer cell behaviour during metastasis (the spread of tumours around the human body).
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1994 an ICR team led by Michael Stratton discovered the gene BRCA2, which has been linked to breast cancer, prostate cancer and ovarian cancer.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Alan Ashworth's team in the Breakthrough Breast Cancer Research Centre at the ICR established the connection between mutations in the BRCA2 gene and the operation of DNA repair pathways in cancer cells.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] This later led to the development of a PARP inhibitor drug, olaparib, which targets the DNA repair pathways of cancer cells.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] A Phase I trial of olaparib found in June 2009 that tumours shrank or stabilised for more than half of patients with BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] It is believed that the drug may also be useful in other patients whose cancer it is linked to an error in their DNA repair pathway.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 1999 the Chester Beatty Laboratory in Chelsea was redeveloped and extended to incorporate the Breakthrough Toby Robins Breast Cancer Research Centre, which was opened by the Prince of Wales in 1999.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In 2000 Michael Stratton at the ICR initiated the Cancer Genome Project, which was aimed at capitalizing on the knowledge from the Human Genome sequence to screen all human genes in cancer cells to identify those genes responsible for specific cancers.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The project was established at the genome sequencing facilities of the Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute near Cambridge, of which Stratton is now the director.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] One of the first major achievements of the Cancer Genome Project has been the characterisation of the cancer gene BRAF in collaboration with ICR scientists Professors Chris Marshall and Richard Marais.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The research by the ICR team, published in June 2002, revealed that damage to the BRAF gene could cause up to 70 per cent of melanoma skin cancers.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] This has been instrumental in speeding up the development of new drugs for the treatment of melanoma.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Since 2002 the ICR has been working to develop drugs that inhibit BRAF in melanoma and other cancers where the gene is defective.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In the five years from 2004/05, the ICR developed on average two drug development candidates per year.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Since 2006, it has licensed three novel series of anti-cancer drugs to major pharmaceutical companies: Hsp90 inhibitors to Novartis, PKB inhibitors to AstraZeneca and PI3Kinase inhibitors to Genentech.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The PIl3Kinase inhibitor GDC-0941, licensed to Genentech by Piramed, is thought to have potential in a range of human cancers.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In laboratory experiments, ICR scientists found that the drug reduced the growth of glioblastoma (the most common form of brain tumour), it decreased the growth of ovarian tumours and in other studies, it was active against cell lines derived from other human cancers.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In conjunction with The Royal Marsden NHS Foundation Trust, the ICR tested a promising new prostate cancer drug called abiraterone, which it discovered and developed.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] A randomised placebo-controlled Phase III trial reported in October 2010 that abiraterone could extend survival in some men with late stage prostate cancer.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The trial, funded by Janssen Pharmaceutical Companies, included 1,195 patients from 13 countries whose advanced prostate cancer had stopped responding to standard therapies.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] Abiraterone extended the average overall survival of patients from 10.9 months to 14.8 months compared to a placebo, without many of the unpleasant side-effects associated with conventional chemotherapy.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The FDA in April 2011 approved the drug for sale in the US under the trade name Zytiga.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In May 2026 staff voted to take industrial strike action for the first time in the institution's history.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] This was due to six years of below inflation pay increases that had left research staff with an effective 16% pay cut.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] In the same period CEO, Kristian Helin, had increased his own pay by over 40% to more than £457,000 per year.
[src:regius-professor/institute-of-cancer-research] The institute's development fund is more than £100 million and the cost of a 16% pay restoration has been costed at only £9 million.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] A **Regius Professor** is a university professor who has, or originally had, royal patronage or appointment.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] They are a unique feature of academia in the United Kingdom and Ireland.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] The first Regius Professorship was in the field of medicine, and founded by the Scottish King James IV at the University of Aberdeen in 1497.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] Regius chairs have since been instituted in various universities, in disciplines judged to be fundamental and for which there is a continuing and significant need.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] This royal imprimatur, and the relative rarity of these professorships, means a Regius chair is prestigious and highly sought after.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] Regius Professors are traditionally addressed as "Regius" and not "Professor".
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] The University of Glasgow currently has the highest number of extant Regius chairs, at fourteen.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] Traditionally, Regius Chairs only existed in the seven ancient universities of the UK and Ireland.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] In October 2012 it was announced that Queen Elizabeth II would create up to six new Regius Professorships, to be announced in early 2013, to mark her Diamond Jubilee.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] In January 2013 the full list was announced, comprising twelve new chairs, probably the largest number ever created in one year, and more than created in most centuries.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] In July 2015 it was announced that further Regius Professorships would be created to mark the Queen's 90th birthday.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] The first Professor of Greek (1708) at Edinburgh, Wiliam Scott *Primus*, was referred to with the honorific 'Regius Professor' but was, ultimately, unable to secure a grant from the Crown.
[src:regius-professor/regius-professor] However, both of the inaugural professors of Greek and Humanity at Edinburgh were appointed by Royal Warrant.
